00:00:42.560 --> 00:00:46.404
but the question
which came up is

00:00:46.404 --> 00:00:47.820
you have two
harmonic oscillators.

00:00:51.370 --> 00:00:54.010
One harmonic oscillator
is in the ground state,

00:00:54.010 --> 00:00:57.290
one is in the excited state.

00:00:57.290 --> 00:01:02.970
And then you have the
harmonic oscillators

00:01:02.970 --> 00:01:09.640
where the excitation
is here and there.

00:01:09.640 --> 00:01:12.660
Is that an entangled
state or not?

00:01:16.460 --> 00:01:17.335
It's a real question.

00:01:30.550 --> 00:01:32.250
I want to think about it.

00:01:32.250 --> 00:01:34.831
AUDIENCE: What's the physical
nature of these oscillators?

00:01:34.831 --> 00:01:36.604
AUDIENCE: Can you
distinguish these?

00:01:36.604 --> 00:01:37.520
WOLFGANG KETTERLE: OK.

00:01:37.520 --> 00:01:40.130
Who's working with ion types?

00:01:40.130 --> 00:01:43.360
There's a few people I know,
a few ion types here at MIT.

00:01:43.360 --> 00:01:49.444
If this is ion-- what is
a good ion? [INAUDIBLE]?

00:01:49.444 --> 00:01:50.360
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:01:50.360 --> 00:01:51.943
WOLFGANG KETTERLE:
Strontium plus, OK.

00:01:51.943 --> 00:01:56.560
So if it's strontium plus, which
can be in the quantum state v

00:01:56.560 --> 00:02:03.090
equals 1 or v equals 0, and you
have another strontium plus ion

00:02:03.090 --> 00:02:06.940
in a second ion
[INAUDIBLE]-- and it can be

00:02:06.940 --> 00:02:09.590
in the [INAUDIBLE]
first excited state--

00:02:09.590 --> 00:02:11.110
isn't it wonderfully entangled?

00:02:11.110 --> 00:02:13.430
Two systems far away.

00:02:13.430 --> 00:02:16.360
You can manipulate them, you
have two particles, and then

00:02:16.360 --> 00:02:17.490
two quantum states.

00:02:17.490 --> 00:02:21.460
It fulfills with flying
colors all the qualities

00:02:21.460 --> 00:02:25.710
you want to see of
an entangled state.

00:02:25.710 --> 00:02:30.120
But now I can say, if I call
this harmonic oscillator,

00:02:30.120 --> 00:02:34.010
I have two optical fibers.

00:02:34.010 --> 00:02:37.890
And you know, a single-mode
fiber defines a harmonic

00:02:37.890 --> 00:02:40.270
oscillator, namely the
electromagnetic field

00:02:40.270 --> 00:02:42.000
in the single mode.

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:45.880
And if I put one
excitation into this fiber,

00:02:45.880 --> 00:02:49.550
I have a photon here and
here I have zero photon.

00:02:49.550 --> 00:02:53.660
Or here, I have one photon
and I have zero photons.

00:02:53.660 --> 00:02:56.350
So if you look at
the fiber, you would

00:02:56.350 --> 00:02:58.550
say the fiber has two states.

00:02:58.550 --> 00:03:01.290
It can have an
excitation or not.

00:03:01.290 --> 00:03:05.470
And if you use now that
approach, you would say,

00:03:05.470 --> 00:03:10.760
well, I have an entangled
state between two fibers.

00:03:10.760 --> 00:03:14.920
However, I can realize
exactly that state

00:03:14.920 --> 00:03:20.070
by having a beam splitter,
by having one photon coming

00:03:20.070 --> 00:03:22.750
on the beam splitter,
and then the photon

00:03:22.750 --> 00:03:27.210
is coupled into
one of the fibers.

00:03:27.210 --> 00:03:29.700
So in other words,
there is an ambiguity

00:03:29.700 --> 00:03:33.990
which I want to point out
between whether you have

00:03:33.990 --> 00:03:37.880
a state of one particle--
one photon into two fibers--

00:03:37.880 --> 00:03:40.000
or whether you have
two fibers which

00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:42.220
can be in two different states.

00:03:42.220 --> 00:03:46.430
So there is often an ambiguity,
what do you call the state

00:03:46.430 --> 00:03:49.470
and what do you
call the particle?

00:03:49.470 --> 00:03:51.840
So at our lunch
conversation it came up

00:03:51.840 --> 00:03:57.070
in a somewhat different context,
but people would actually

00:03:57.070 --> 00:04:01.070
say that splitting
a photon-- sending

00:04:01.070 --> 00:04:03.480
one photon across
a beam splitter

00:04:03.480 --> 00:04:06.240
fulfills, if you
interpret it in that way,

00:04:06.240 --> 00:04:09.350
fulfills the definition
of entanglement.

00:04:09.350 --> 00:04:12.680
I know our wiki page and
Professor Schwan would probably

00:04:12.680 --> 00:04:16.529
not agree, but welcome to
the frontier of research

00:04:16.529 --> 00:04:18.990
where different people
have different opinions

00:04:18.990 --> 00:04:23.950
and certain definitions
are still being worked out.

00:04:23.950 --> 00:04:25.580
But there is one
thing which is real.

00:04:29.160 --> 00:04:31.420
We have here two different
harmonic oscillators,

00:04:31.420 --> 00:04:35.340
ions oscillating in a harmonic
oscillator potential or photons

00:04:35.340 --> 00:04:36.940
in a single mode.

00:04:36.940 --> 00:04:40.470
I remember from 15
years ago, there

00:04:40.470 --> 00:04:45.550
were papers that show if you
put the ion in a cavity or such,

00:04:45.550 --> 00:04:47.640
you can really
transfer the quantum

00:04:47.640 --> 00:04:52.290
state from the single
photon from this harmonic

00:04:52.290 --> 00:04:54.520
oscillator-- the
harmonic oscillator

00:04:54.520 --> 00:04:56.710
of the electromagnetic
field-- to the harmonic

00:04:56.710 --> 00:04:59.140
oscillator of the ion.

00:04:59.140 --> 00:05:02.960
So if we want to hold
onto the definition,

00:05:02.960 --> 00:05:07.090
which I'm not sure if you should
that this is a single photon,

00:05:07.090 --> 00:05:09.300
a single particle
cannot be entangled,

00:05:09.300 --> 00:05:12.655
well I know and people reminded
me at lunch the there is

00:05:12.655 --> 00:05:18.220
a protocol to [INAUDIBLE] map
the single photon in the two

00:05:18.220 --> 00:05:21.910
modes after the beam splitter
onto an entangled state

00:05:21.910 --> 00:05:23.860
of ions.

00:05:23.860 --> 00:05:26.790
So if you focus here on
the photon and say a single

00:05:26.790 --> 00:05:30.100
