00:12:03.510 --> 00:12:07.910
So the situation
is the following,

00:12:07.910 --> 00:12:12.940
we want to entangle two atoms.

00:12:12.940 --> 00:12:15.140
We have two atoms which
are both in the excited

00:12:15.140 --> 00:12:16.520
state in the scatter light.

00:12:19.210 --> 00:12:24.100
And they can go to two
different ground states.

00:12:24.100 --> 00:12:26.150
Think about two different
type of ion states.

00:12:26.150 --> 00:12:29.550
I call them U and
D, Up and Down.

00:12:29.550 --> 00:12:32.790
And when because
of selection rules,

00:12:32.790 --> 00:12:35.112
one state can be reached
with one polarization.

00:12:35.112 --> 00:12:37.570
The other state can be reached
with the other polarization.

00:12:37.570 --> 00:12:42.520
And I call this polarization H
and V, horizontal and vertical.

00:12:42.520 --> 00:12:44.890
In reality, this will be
circular polarization,

00:12:44.890 --> 00:12:48.210
so you may want to transform
from linear to circular

00:12:48.210 --> 00:12:48.870
after the fact.

00:12:48.870 --> 00:12:51.250
But for just the
discussion right now,

00:12:51.250 --> 00:12:54.270
I assume that horizontal
polarization leads

00:12:54.270 --> 00:12:56.460
to one state,
vertical polarization

00:12:56.460 --> 00:12:58.190
leads to the other state.

00:12:58.190 --> 00:13:03.620
So therefore, if you have
two atoms-- and Chris Monroe

00:13:03.620 --> 00:13:06.120
in Michigan did the
experiment where he really

00:13:06.120 --> 00:13:08.240
had two different
vacuum chambers with two

00:13:08.240 --> 00:13:11.020
different ions, they
both emitted photons,

00:13:11.020 --> 00:13:13.627
and then the photons came
together on a beam splitter.

00:13:13.627 --> 00:13:15.960
So that's what you should
sort of have in mind, two ions

00:13:15.960 --> 00:13:16.980
here and there.

00:13:16.980 --> 00:13:18.760
They both emit a photon.

00:13:18.760 --> 00:13:26.820
And after the have
both emitted a photon,

00:13:26.820 --> 00:13:30.450
each ion is in a
superposition before you

00:13:30.450 --> 00:13:31.750
make any measurements.

00:13:31.750 --> 00:13:34.360
It can be in up with
a horizontal photon

00:13:34.360 --> 00:13:36.400
or it can be in down
with a vertical photon.

00:13:36.400 --> 00:13:39.520
So that is the state of the ion.

00:13:39.520 --> 00:13:43.735
And so we have two of those.

00:13:46.340 --> 00:13:48.560
And then you want
to detect photons.

00:13:48.560 --> 00:13:51.310
And the goal now is by
using beam splitters and all

00:13:51.310 --> 00:13:54.460
those tricks, that the
detection of photons

00:13:54.460 --> 00:13:58.180
and the outcome of a measurement
will project this product

00:13:58.180 --> 00:14:01.440
state of two atoms
with their photon

00:14:01.440 --> 00:14:04.300
into a bell state for the atoms.

00:14:04.300 --> 00:14:06.280
So measurement on
photons can take

00:14:06.280 --> 00:14:08.380
two atoms which were
completely remote,

00:14:08.380 --> 00:14:10.070
had nothing to do
with each other,

00:14:10.070 --> 00:14:12.390
and suddenly they're
in a Bell state.

00:14:12.390 --> 00:14:16.000
And this is done by the
probabalistic measurement.

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:37.130
And so let's-- so
lets develop it.

00:14:41.920 --> 00:14:55.660
Our initial state is UH plus DV.

00:14:59.220 --> 00:15:01.390
This is system one.

00:15:01.390 --> 00:15:07.360
And we have the direct product
with our second ion trap

00:15:07.360 --> 00:15:10.600
apparatus which
has done the same.

00:15:10.600 --> 00:15:13.610
The ion has emitted a photon and
we don't know anything about it

00:15:13.610 --> 00:15:15.530
at this point.

00:15:15.530 --> 00:15:18.086
And now it is important, if you
want to have entanglement you

00:15:18.086 --> 00:15:19.710
cannot go and measure
the polarization,

00:15:19.710 --> 00:15:23.045
because this would project an
individual ion into a state

00:15:23.045 --> 00:15:24.750
and would not have entangled it.

00:15:24.750 --> 00:15:30.280
So what we are doing is we
are allowing the two photons,

00:15:30.280 --> 00:15:34.250
one photon here,
another photon here,

00:15:34.250 --> 00:15:36.360
they come together
at a beam splitter.

00:15:41.170 --> 00:15:45.700
Actually, before I do it let me
just perform the product here.

00:15:45.700 --> 00:15:51.380
So what we get is-- well,
it's just multiplying it out.

00:15:51.380 --> 00:15:56.900
UU for the atoms,
HH for the photons.

00:15:56.900 --> 00:16:07.986
UDHV plus DUVH, plus DDVV.

00:16:11.420 --> 00:16:13.790
So what you want
to do is we want

00:16:13.790 --> 00:16:18.110
to send this beam--
the photons of course,

00:16:18.110 --> 00:16:22.400
the atoms stay put--
onto a beam splitter.

00:16:22.400 --> 00:16:27.050
Now, I can do it more rigorously
by keeping all the terms

00:16:27.050 --> 00:16:29.080
until the end of
the calculation.

00:16:29.080 --> 00:16:33.390
But I hope it's rather obvious
that we want to have it--

00:16:33.390 --> 00:16:35.200
if we want to send
it on a beam splitter

00:16:35.200 --> 00:16:39.080
and then we want to detect
that both detectors make click.

00:16:39.080 --> 00:16:42.750
That requires the photons
to be distinguishable.

00:16:42.750 --> 00:16:45.760
So therefore, those
two terms will not

00:16:45.760 --> 00:16:48.670
contribute because the photons
have the same polarization.

00:16:58.890 --> 00:17:04.599
So we are now using a
protective measurement.

00:17:04.599 --> 00:17:08.985
We want to find out what is
the wave function of the atoms.

00:17:13.079 --> 00:17:26.640
Measurement of one photon
in the modes A and B,

00:17:26.640 --> 00:17:30.040
which are the output modes
of our beam splitter.

00:17:36.040 --> 00:17:45.310
So it needs one more line.

00:17:45.310 --> 00:17:50.610
The output of the
beam splitter is--

00:17:50.610 --> 00:17:59.920
so I'm only focusing now on the
two terms which can give rise

00:17:59.920 --> 00:18:04.660
to two clicks at the
two different detectors.

00:18:04.660 --> 00:18:12.000
So I will factor out UD.

00:18:12.000 --> 00:18:17.520
And now we have the two photons
hitting the beam splitter

00:18:17.520 --> 00:18:22.170
and each photon goes into
a 50/50 superposition.

00:18:22.170 --> 00:18:27.360
So I take know this
horizontal photon.

00:18:30.837 --> 00:18:33.045
And since we don't mess
around with the polarization,

00:18:33.045 --> 00:18:37.010
it's still a horizontal
photon, but the photon

00:18:37.010 --> 00:18:46.620
can be now in mode B or in
mode A in one of the output

00:18:46.620 --> 00:18:50.080
modes of the beam splitter.

00:18:50.080 --> 00:19:02.610
And I label that
as 0,1 plus 1,0.

00:19:02.610 --> 00:19:11.640
Now for the second photon, it
had a vertical polarization,

00:19:11.640 --> 00:19:16.190
so it's a vertical photon.

00:19:16.190 --> 00:19:20.630
The second photon is coming
onto the beam splitter

00:19:20.630 --> 00:19:23.156
in the other input port,
because we have taken the two

00:19:23.156 --> 00:19:24.780
photons from two
different experiments,

00:19:24.780 --> 00:19:26.404
from two different
experimental setups,

00:19:26.404 --> 00:19:30.250
and now we combine
them so that we'll also

00:19:30.250 --> 00:19:33.830
be now in a superposition
of 0,1 and 1,0.

00:19:33.830 --> 00:19:37.775
But you know that one mode
transforms with a plus sign

00:19:37.775 --> 00:19:40.400
and the other mode transforms at
the beam splitter with a minus

00:19:40.400 --> 00:19:40.899
sign.

00:19:44.010 --> 00:19:46.450
So that's how you should
look at those terms.

00:19:46.450 --> 00:19:51.500
And of course, from of
this here, from this term

00:19:51.500 --> 00:20:05.090
we get something very
analogous, 0,1 plus 1,0.

00:20:05.090 --> 00:20:08.850
And for the other
spatial mode, the minus

00:20:08.850 --> 00:20:14.540
sign from the beam
splitter, 1,0.

00:20:14.540 --> 00:20:16.110
OK, now we are done.

00:20:16.110 --> 00:20:19.690
Now we are detecting photons.

00:20:19.690 --> 00:20:22.620
So we want to look at this
wave function and ask,

00:20:22.620 --> 00:20:26.830
what happens if in port
A-- the output port--

00:20:26.830 --> 00:20:31.522
we find one horizontal photon,
and in B it must be vertical

00:20:31.522 --> 00:20:33.480
because the photons have
to be distinguishable.

00:20:36.980 --> 00:20:42.650
So where do we have
one photon in mode A?

00:20:42.650 --> 00:20:46.370
In horizontal it is here.

00:20:46.370 --> 00:20:50.540
And here it is this
product with the minus sign

00:20:50.540 --> 00:20:55.180
where we have-- no,
sorry, the plus sign.

00:20:55.180 --> 00:20:57.160
Here we have one
photon in the vertical,

00:20:57.160 --> 00:20:59.270
so this is with a plus sign.

00:20:59.270 --> 00:21:01.400
But we have a
second possibility,

00:21:01.400 --> 00:21:11.470
one photon in mode A horizontal
happens here with a minus sign.

00:21:11.470 --> 00:21:17.090
And one photon in mode
B vertical happens here.

00:21:17.090 --> 00:21:21.710
So in other words, form
the term which gives rise

00:21:21.710 --> 00:21:25.680
to this measurement process,
we have a plus UD here,

00:21:25.680 --> 00:21:30.680
and because of the
minus sign, a minus DU.

00:21:30.680 --> 00:21:34.600
So therefore, if
you would detect

00:21:34.600 --> 00:21:37.020
the photon with the polarization
at this point, which

00:21:37.020 --> 00:21:45.030
we don't do, this polarization
gives rise to UD minus DU.

00:21:45.030 --> 00:21:50.870
We have a second possibility to
have a click at each detector,

00:21:50.870 --> 00:21:52.955
and this is when we reverse
the two polarizations.

00:21:55.910 --> 00:22:00.390
But in this case, you can
just add the wave function.

00:22:00.390 --> 00:22:09.126
You get the atomic state,
the sign doesn't matter.

00:22:09.126 --> 00:22:11.750
So you have to measurements, two
possibilities in polarization,

00:22:11.750 --> 00:22:13.705
but they both have
the same outcome.

00:22:16.690 --> 00:22:23.730
They generate this state, so
the result of all that is I've

00:22:23.730 --> 00:22:31.510
shown you that the two
atoms are left now in--

00:22:31.510 --> 00:22:35.520
and now I put back in the
correct normalization--

00:22:35.520 --> 00:22:40.850
in one of the Bell states.

00:22:40.850 --> 00:22:48.140
So whenever you detect the two
single photons in coincidence

00:22:48.140 --> 00:22:50.410
on both counters,
at that moment you

00:22:50.410 --> 00:22:54.320
know what you have is
an entangled state,

00:22:54.320 --> 00:22:55.480
a Bell state of atoms.

00:22:58.200 --> 00:23:02.660
Now, the big issue
here is efficiency.

00:23:02.660 --> 00:23:05.360
Your photon detectors
are not highly efficient.

00:23:05.360 --> 00:23:08.825
And I was sort of only
looking at combinations

00:23:08.825 --> 00:23:11.610
where we have this
double detection.

00:23:11.610 --> 00:23:14.760
Most components of
the wave function

00:23:14.760 --> 00:23:17.430
will give the
Hong-Ou-Mandel effect.

00:23:17.430 --> 00:23:19.210
The two photons go in one way.

00:23:19.210 --> 00:23:21.890
So therefore, you have
to prepare your system,

00:23:21.890 --> 00:23:24.760
have photons emitted,
and in most of the cases

00:23:24.760 --> 00:23:26.280
you will not get
the state you want,

00:23:26.280 --> 00:23:28.220
so you have to keep on trying.

00:23:28.220 --> 00:23:30.590
And usually those
experiments are

00:23:30.590 --> 00:23:35.430
heavily limited by the very,
very dismal success probability

00:23:35.430 --> 00:23:37.670
of creating the state you want.

00:23:37.670 --> 00:23:40.550
And when you want to extend
it, not just to two atoms

00:23:40.550 --> 00:23:44.520
entangled, to three atoms
and four atoms entangled,

00:23:44.520 --> 00:23:48.400
then you get a smaller
number to the power n

00:23:48.400 --> 00:23:49.910
for your efficiency.

00:23:49.910 --> 00:23:53.990
So this probabalistic
preparation doesn't scale up,

00:23:53.990 --> 00:23:58.410
but it is a very simple scheme,
it's a very powerful scheme,

00:23:58.410 --> 00:24:07.700
and it has been used to create
teleportation of atomic states

00:24:07.700 --> 00:24:13.555
and do some tests of Bells
inequality and the EPR Paradox.

00:24:16.592 --> 00:24:21.990
And here is the
abstract of a paper.

00:24:21.990 --> 00:24:27.280
So-- well, this was just
2008, so just a few years ago.

00:24:27.280 --> 00:24:37.940
And what you see here is
that here are one meter apart

00:24:37.940 --> 00:24:40.480
two [INAUDIBLE] ions.

